Correction: my ADHD medication is recently on the PBS which means it’s $40+ instead of $100+. Still prohibitively expensive for lots of people though, never mind the costs of diagnosis and checkups.
@mat_3rd The ADHD med is only a recent addition to the PBS which takes it down from $100+ to $40+ a month. The migraine med is on the PBS at a lower dose but not at mine.
@WayTooFunnyRN @realDeanCool I’m on sumatriptan but 100mg tablets instead of 50mg, so it’s a private script; works out the same cost as 2x50s though

The cheapest option is $40+ a month for ADHD meds and $10 per tablet for migraine meds. I earn well above the median wage so I can afford it but I think people most people would struggle. Both are crucial to improving my quality of life and protecting my health.

I am a relatively healthy young person but I have two chronic health conditions - ADHD and migraines. Both are incredibly common and well controlled with standard medications but those meds aren’t on the PBS. Australian healthcare isn’t universal (and it should be).

@johnnytrashbag This is exciting! I am biased because I am the type of kid this would have been good for - I am not great at sitting quietly and focussing during lectures.

And we now have the online infrastructure at plenty of schools, so it’s a matter of method. It is very important to note that I am NOT  a teacher and I am NOT qualified to suggest these things at all. I’m just interested. If you’re interested, listen to your teachers.

Also it sets a hard limit on how much work students have to do outside of school so they can, like, sleep and have hobbies and grow their social skills. Also kids with limited mobility etc can catch up on the concepts side at their leisure.

I know it’s been trialled in the US and I suspect elsewhere. It obviously wouldn’t suit everyone but I think it would be a particular benefit for kids of big families and non-English speakers where “just ask your parents” is not an easy or helpful way to do homework.

I am not qualified to comment on education BUT I would like to see some high schools trial the “flipped” school day when this is over. The idea is that your “homework” is a short video lecture and then you do the practice work/applied learning in class when you can ask questions.

@aliceleung @JaneCaro Also most students won’t need one-on-one help, so you could have your key classes and then free study periods for them to catch up where they need. Then it’s fewer teachers onsite.

This long thread is to say that if you’re able to give blood (not everyone is, you can check online), consider doing it! It’s an excuse to leave the house and it’s just a nice way to spend a little time helping people without doing much at all. #giveblood #lifeblood

The @lifebloodau professionals are always incredibly lovely and efficient, and very hospitable! I like to read or listen to a podcast, and try not to fall sleep because it’s actually very comfy. Whole blood is much faster and you can give every couple of months 👌🏻

I’ve had to take breaks of months at a time due to illness or whatever, but I keep coming back. The weird thing is that I genuinely enjoy it? Plasma takes about 2 hours for me (it’s different for different people) and it’s just like an enforced chill out that also helps.
So I give blood (plasma) every two weeks. I started a few years ago giving whole blood after my dad had heart surgery and I realised it was an easy way to help other people going through that.
